The rifles themselves are unique, as on the wrist of the rifle is a Tigers Head, that represented “The Wild Tiger Corp”.  This also comes with a Pattern 1907 bayonet which are getting very difficult to find as well.  Don't miss out on this one!  There are very few left since the Japanese destroyed most of them during WWII and the climate did the rest!Price:  750.00

title: For Sale:  7.62x51 / .308 Plastic Training Ammunition
location: Apex, Raleigh / Durham / CH, North Carolina
postcontent: This is a bit of an oddball. These are plastic-cased, plastic-bullet'd rounds intended for training on non-full-size ranges, but they're great for back yard plinking as well. The bullet/case seem to be a unitary casting of plastic, with a metal base and primer somehow attached to the bottom. That primer, and maybe a little bit of powder, are enough to break off the 10gr-11gr bullet along a seam, and downrange it goes. These ARE lethal, and should be treated as such. They are NOT simmunitions. Not guaranteed to cycle any semi-automatic firearms. Price is per box, and I have two boxes of 500 rounds each.

The Remington 788 has two distinguishing design features. The first is the rear-lugged bolt. The bolt has nine lugs in three rows of three lugs each. They lock into the receiver behind the magazine well. Due to this design, the bolt handle lifts only 60 degrees on opening giving more clearance for scopes compared to the 90 degrees required for the Model 700 and other two-lug rifles. The bolt travel is also reduced because of the rear lugs.
